msContents.summary: This manuscript on paper is an early-fifteenth-century copy of Thomas Hoccleve, De regimine principum in English verse, and John Walton's translation of Boethius' De consolatione philosophiae, in English verse. The colophon for the latter (fol. 177v) is signed by a certain John Tebaud "alias Watyrbeach," who may be identifiable with John Walton himself, and dated to 1410. A marginal portrait of Chaucer is included on fol. 70v.

msItem.title: Regiment of princes; Consolation of philosophy
msItem.author: Hoccleve, Thomas, 1370?-1450?
Boethius, -524
msItem.colophon: Explicit liber Boecii de consolacione philosophie de Latino in Anglicum translatus Anno domini Millesimo CCCC Xo per Capellanum Iohannem Tebaud alias Watyrbeche [fol. 177v]

msItem.title: Thomas Hoccleve, De Regimine Principum
msItem.incipit: MVsyng vp on the restles bisynesse / Which that this world hath ay on honde… [fol. 1r]
msItem.explicit: …Of hevenes blysse that is endeles / To which yow brynge thauctour of pees [fol. 77r]

msItem.title: Envoy to the De Regimine Principum
msItem.incipit: A [sic] lityl book who yaf the hardynesse / Thy wordys to pronounce in the presence… [fol. 77r]
msItem.explicit: …To the that al seyst of lovis servence / That knoweth he that no thyng is hid fro. [fol. 77v]

msItem.title: Interpellation of missing verses from the De Regimine Principum
Beothius, De consolatione philosophiae, trans. John Walton
msItem.incipit: INsuffisaunce of kunnyng and of wyt / Defaute of langage and of eloquence… [fol. 78r]
msItem.explicit: …Vn to the presence off the Iuge on hye / That al thyng dooth beholde plenerlye [fol. 177v]

supportDesc.extent: ii+177+iii; 276 x 201 mm bound to 288 x 212 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation, in pencil, upper right

p.signatures: Alphanumerical signatures on lower right recto of the first half of leaves in each gathering, a-k (fols. 1-76); a-n (fols. 77-177)

p.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords centered in lower margin at folios 8v, 16v, 24v, 32v, 40v, 46v, 54v, 62v, 70v, 85v, 93v, 101v, 109v, 117v, 125v, 133v, 141v, 149v, 157v, 165v, 175v

layoutDesc.layout: One column with wide margins, thirty-five lines (divided into five groups of seven lines); unruled; the chain lines of the paper used as a guide for the left side of the text; red two- and three-line initials throughout; written area: approximately 185 x 108 mm

decoDesc.decoNote: Portrait of Chaucer, a tinted drawing, fol. 70v

binding.p: Eighteenth-century leather cover boards; front and back covers detached; spine cracked

history.provenance: Charles Yarnold (sold 1825); collection of Sir Thomas Phillipps, n. 1099, with his stamp on recto of second upper flyleaf; purchased by Rosenbach in 1923
